<!-- TOP FAILURES -->
<section class="section section-gray">
  <div class="container">
    <p class="section-number">02, Top Range Failures</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">What our techs see most often, in rough order of frequency</h2>
    <p class="lead">Eight failure modes account for nearly every commercial range call we run. The first four are routine wear and inexpensive. The bottom three are the conversations where we sometimes recommend major service over piecemeal repair.</p>

    <div class="failures-list">
      <div class="failure-row">
        <div class="num">1</div>
        <div>
          <h3>Igniter failure (year 4–7)</h3>
          <p>Pilot or electronic ignition wear, the single most common range call. Vulcan and Garland use different ignition systems with different failure signatures. Replacement runs $260–$440 per burner. We carry the common Vulcan and Garland igniters on the van.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="failure-row">
        <div class="num">2</div>
        <div>
          <h3>Thermocouple wear (year 5–8)</h3>
          <p>Safety device that shuts off the gas if the pilot extinguishes. When it fails, the burner ignites and then shuts down within seconds. Replacement $220–$340. Don't bypass it.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="failure-row">
        <div class="num">3</div>
        <div>
          <h3>Burner head clog</h3>
          <p>Grease and food carbon build into the burner head over months of service. Cleaning service $180–$290 per burner, no parts needed if caught before the orifice fully blocks.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="failure-row">
        <div class="num">4</div>
        <div>
          <h3>Oven thermostat drift</h3>
          <p>Temperature accuracy degrades, the displayed 350°F is actually 320°F or 390°F at the rack. Calibration first if the mechanism is sound ($290–$540), full replacement if drifted past calibration range.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="failure-row">
        <div class="num">5</div>
        <div>
          <h3>Door gasket compression</h3>
          <p>Heat seal degrades from years of door slams and thermal cycling. Once it leaks, the oven works harder and uneven cooking shows up before the gas bill does. Replacement $290–$540.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="failure-row">
        <div class="num">6</div>
        <div>
          <h3>Salamander broiler igniter</h3>
          <p>Heavy-use restaurant ranges with integrated salamander above the burner top. Same igniter category as a burner igniter, $260–$440, but mounted in a hotter zone so wear shows up earlier. Few shops in LA take salamander work; we do.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="failure-row">
        <div class="num">7</div>
        <div>
          <h3>Gas valve failure (year 10+)</h3>
          <p>Less common, more expensive. Full gas valve replacement $580–$980. When a 12-year-old range has its third gas valve fail in 18 months, the conversation shifts toward a major rebuild or replacement.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="failure-row">
        <div class="num">8</div>
        <div>
          <h3>Convection fan motor (if convection oven)</h3>
          <p>Year 7–10 on ranges with convection in the oven cavity. Motor replacement $480–$720. Bearings give the audible warning a few months out, worth scheduling proactively.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

